{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/pubic-lice/background-information/cause/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"0a849f5f-c58d-5123-b67a-2ed2ed5785e2","slug":"cause","fullItemName":"Cause","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 9f001cf6-2559-4881-82f7-19ecb977d967 --><h2>What causes pubic lice infestation?</h2><!-- end field 9f001cf6-2559-4881-82f7-19ecb977d967 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 02ffc4aa-8c88-42eb-9a25-786ad47b8ec7 --><!-- begin field b822e978-227a-48e0-879d-6c69d5bbc2d8 --><ul><li><strong>Pubic lice infestation (pediculosis pubis) is caused by an obligate, blood-sucking ectoparasite — <em>Phthirus pubis</em></strong>.<ul><li><em>P. pubis</em> is also known as the crab louse due to pincer-like claws on its second and third pairs of legs. These claws allow the louse to attach to coarse body hair, most often in the pubic area, but also occasionally on the chest, armpits, eyelashes and face.</li><li>The pubic louse is grey-brown in colour and about 2 mm long and can only survive for 24–48 hours off the human host.</li><li>Female lice live for 1–3 months and over this time can lay up to 300 yellow/white eggs which are smaller than a pinhead. The eggs are attached to the base of hair shafts and hatch and mature into adult lice within 20 days. Empty eggshells (nits) remain tightly attached to the hair and cannot be brushed off.</li></ul></li><li>Direct contact is required for transmission of <em>P. pubis</em> as the lice cannot fly or jump from host to host.<ul><li>The most common route of transmission is sexual or non-sexual close body contact but lice may also crawl onto a host from infested materials such as bedding, clothing or towels.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Gunning, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Public Health Agency of Canada, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">RCGP, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Markova, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Dadabhoy, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Primary Care Dermatology Society, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Salavastru, 2017</a>]</p><!-- end field b822e978-227a-48e0-879d-6c69d5bbc2d8 --><!-- end item 02ffc4aa-8c88-42eb-9a25-786ad47b8ec7 -->","topic":{"id":"d9c800be-d493-5d1c-81c1-7e9ac00d0e91","topicId":"01c7ac76-ef6e-42b7-836c-ff538154f62a","topicName":"Pubic lice","slug":"pubic-lice","lastRevised":"Last revised in February 2018","chapters":[{"id":"e84df283-1ddd-5fec-bb06-50027c460ccb","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"b002a6cc-4c38-5629-b392-ddb39ece58b7","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"8c0a40c3-6240-572e-91c8-9c9832c437f7","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"75c14179-33ce-5f2a-811b-f8d43efb1dff","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"7251900b-7e07-51b6-9864-ce5feacb2549","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"9f11ff42-e98f-52ed-ad50-7ccb91b78747","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"48aa5dc5-ebb5-5204-9cce-98fa93e1fffe","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"7a514fc4-ac3c-5ece-bdb5-72cb57102cab","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"6b51f8aa-d337-50c3-84ee-7ddb0ec0a260","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"4d7ae4f3-6c68-5774-afc7-f19a2b8d